---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { files, aggregates, leanRepo, ghFile } from '../data/proofs';

const {
  verifiedOriginal, totalStatements, mathlibWrappers, supportingLemmas,
  cleanFiles, partialFiles, sorriesTotal, flagshipCount, totalFiles,
} = aggregates;

// JSON-LD emits every flagship as a CreativeWork with its Lean source in `text`.
const theoremLd = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "ItemList",
  name: "Machine-verified Lean theorems — Monogate",
  numberOfItems: flagshipCount,
  itemListElement: files.flatMap((f, fi) =>
    f.flagships.map((th, ti) => ({
      "@type": "ListItem",
      position: fi * 10 + ti + 1,
      item: {
        "@type": "CreativeWork",
        "@id": `https://monogate.org/proofs#${th.name}`,
        name: th.name,
        description: th.hook,
        url: ghFile(f.file, th.line),
        codeRepository: leanRepo,
        programmingLanguage: "Lean 4",
        text: th.source,
        isPartOf: {
          "@type": "SoftwareSourceCode",
          name: f.file,
          codeRepository: leanRepo,
        },
      },
    }))
  ),
};
---

<Base
  title="Machine-Verified Proofs — monogate.org"
  description={`${verifiedOriginal} original EML theorems verified in Lean 4 with full source. ${totalStatements} total statements. Zero sorries across ${cleanFiles} files. Clone the repo, run lake build — no trust required.`}
>
  <div class="meta">
    <span>Lean 4 · Mathlib v4.14.0</span>
    <span>0 sorries across {cleanFiles} files</span>
    <span><a href={leanRepo}>monogate-lean</a></span>
  </div>

  <h1>Machine-Verified Proofs</h1>
  <p class="lead">
    {verifiedOriginal} original theorems verified by computer. {totalStatements} total Lean statements. Zero sorries across {cleanFiles} files.
  </p>

  <section class="verify">
    <div class="verify-head">Verify this yourself</div>
    <pre class="shell"><code>git clone https://github.com/almaguer1986/monogate-lean
cd monogate-lean
lake build
# Build completed successfully. 0 errors. 0 sorries across 13 of 14 files; 2 documented sorries in InfiniteZerosBarrier.lean.</code></pre>
    <p class="verify-note">
      First run takes 2–5 minutes (Mathlib oleans download from the GitHub cache). Runs locally.
      No network verifier, no remote kernel. If <code>lake build</code> exits 0, every theorem on
      this page has been checked from the axioms of type theory up.
    </p>
  </section>

  <div class="divider"></div>

  <h2 id="what-verified-means">What "machine-verified" means</h2>
  <p>
    Lean 4 is a proof assistant that mechanically checks every logical step of every proof against
    the axioms of constructive type theory. It is not a linter. It is not a testing framework.
    The kernel is a small, auditable program that either accepts a proof or rejects it.
  </p>
  <ul class="rules">
    <li>
      <code>sorry</code> is Lean's reserved placeholder for "I admit this without proof." Files
      that contain <code>sorry</code> are explicitly incomplete. <strong>0 sorries = complete verification.</strong>
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>lake build</code> recompiles every proof from source against its declared Mathlib
      version. If any tactic fails, any identifier is missing, or any type error exists, the build
      errors out and prints the location.
    </li>
    <li>
      The guarantee is as strong as the consistency of the Lean kernel's axioms (propositional
      extensionality, function extensionality, quotient types, choice). No authorship, no journal
      venue, no peer review in the guarantee chain.
    </li>
    <li>
      A proof here is <em>not</em> "the author believes." It is <em>"your laptop has checked, step
      by step, that the conclusion follows from the axioms."</em>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <div class="divider"></div>

  <h2 id="breakdown">Honest breakdown</h2>
  <p>The repository contains {totalStatements} named statements. They are not all equally original. Here is the accounting:</p>
  <dl class="breakdown">
    <div><dt>{verifiedOriginal}</dt><dd>EML-original theorems — results specific to this framework (SuperBEST lower bounds, F16-shape witnesses, EMLTree depth hierarchy, ELC preservation, self-map conjugacies).</dd></div>
    <div><dt>{mathlibWrappers}</dt><dd>Mathlib identity wrappers — named aliases of lemmas already in Mathlib, re-exported under EML-readable names (e.g. <code>exp_ln_cancel</code> is <code>Real.exp_log</code>).</dd></div>
    <div><dt>{supportingLemmas}</dt><dd>Supporting lemmas — per-operator witnesses, trivial evaluations, definitional unfolds, and proof scaffolding that feed the originals.</dd></div>
    <div><dt>{totalStatements}</dt><dd>Total verified statements, all 0-sorry except as noted below.</dd></div>
    <div><dt>{sorriesTotal}</dt><dd>Sorry statements, all in <code>InfiniteZerosBarrier.lean</code>: <code>sin_not_in_eml</code> and <code>sin_not_in_real_EML_k</code>. Both flag the same open gap — a quantitative zero-count bound on EML-k trees needs o-minimal structure theory (Wilkie 1996, not yet formalized in Mathlib).</dd></div>
  </dl>

  <div class="divider"></div>

  <h2 id="files">Per-file summary</h2>
  <div class="proof-table" role="region" aria-label="Lean-verified files">
    <div class="proof-head">
      <span>Status</span><span>Theorem</span><span>What it proves</span><span>File</span>
    </div>
    {files.map(f => (
      <div class={`proof-row ${f.ok ? 'ok' : 'partial'}`}>
        <span class="status">
          {f.ok ? (<><span class="check">✓</span> 0 sorries</>) : (<><span class="warn">⚠</span> {f.sorries} sorries</>)}
        </span>
        <span class="thm">{f.thm}</span>
        <span class="what">{f.what}</span>
        <span class="file">
          <a href={ghFile(f.file)}><code>{f.file}</code></a>
          <span class="counts">{f.original} original / {f.total} statements</span>
        </span>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <div class="divider"></div>

  <h2 id="flagship">Flagship theorems — full Lean source</h2>
  <p>
    Below: {flagshipCount} flagship theorems across the {totalFiles} files. Every block is a verbatim copy of the source.
    Each is linked to its GitHub line number. The "<code>by</code>" tactic block is the proof, not a description of the proof.
  </p>

  {files.map(f => (
    <section class={`file-block ${f.ok ? 'ok' : 'partial'}`} id={f.file.replace('.lean', '')}>
      <header class="file-header">
        <h3><code>{f.file}</code></h3>
        <div class="file-meta">
          <span class={`sorry-badge ${f.ok ? 'zero' : 'some'}`}>
            {f.ok ? '✓ 0 sorries' : `⚠ ${f.sorries} sorries (o-minimal, documented)`}
          </span>
          <span class="counts-inline">{f.original} original / {f.total} statements</span>
          <a href={ghFile(f.file)} class="view-gh">view full file →</a>
        </div>
        <p class="file-what">{f.what}</p>
      </header>
      {f.flagships.map(th => (
        <article class={`theorem ${th.hasSorry ? 'has-sorry' : ''}`} id={th.name}>
          <div class="theorem-head">
            <code class="thm-name">{th.name}</code>
            <a href={ghFile(f.file, th.line)} class="line-link">{f.file}:L{th.line} →</a>
          </div>
          <p class="hook">{th.hook}</p>
          {th.hasSorry && (
            <p class="sorry-warn">
              ⚠ Contains <code>sorry</code> — documented open gap. The statement is the T01
              barrier; the missing step is the quantitative zero-count bound for EML-k trees,
              which requires o-minimal structure theory not yet formalized in Mathlib.
            </p>
          )}
          <pre class="lean"><code class="language-lean">{th.source}</code></pre>
        </article>
      ))}
    </section>
  ))}

  <div class="divider"></div>

  <h2 id="scrape">For machines</h2>
  <p>
    Every flagship on this page is wrapped in a <code>&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class="language-lean"&gt;</code> block
    with a stable <code>id</code> anchor (e.g. <a href="#mul_one_node_positive"><code>#mul_one_node_positive</code></a>).
    A plain-text companion dump is available at <a href="/proofs.lean.txt"><code>/proofs.lean.txt</code></a>
    — curl-friendly, no HTML, one <code>-- file:line — name</code> header per theorem.
    The same content is also emitted as <code>CreativeWork</code> entries in this page's
    JSON-LD for structured-data crawlers (view source).
  </p>

  <p class="footnote">
    <strong>On the partial file.</strong> The 2 sorries in <code>InfiniteZerosBarrier.lean</code>
    sit on the final step that connects the analyticity proof to the depth-k zero-count
    bound. This requires o-minimal structure theory (Wilkie 1996) that is not yet
    formalised in Mathlib. The supporting lemmas — <em>sin has infinitely many real
    zeros</em>, <em>EML trees are real-analytic on (0, ∞)</em>, <em>a non-zero real-analytic
    function has finitely many zeros on any compact interval</em> — are all verified with
    0 sorries. The residual gap is a missing Mathlib chapter, not a gap in the argument.
  </p>

  <div class="divider"></div>

  <p style="color: var(--muted); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-top: 32px;">
    {cleanFiles} clean files + {partialFiles} partial · <a href={leanRepo}>monogate-lean repo</a> · paper:
    <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.21852">arXiv:2603.21852</a> · catalog: <a href="/theorems">theorems</a>
  </p>

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(theoremLd)}></script>

  <style>
    .lead {
      color: var(--muted);
      font-style: italic;
      margin: 0 0 28px;
    }

    section.verify {
      margin: 24px 0 28px;
      padding: 18px 22px;
      background: var(--surface);
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-radius: 4px;
    }
    .verify-head {
      font-family: var(--mono);
      font-size: 0.72rem;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 1.5px;
      color: var(--muted);
      margin-bottom: 10px;
    }
    .verify-note {
      font-size: 0.88rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      margin: 10px 0 0;
      line-height: 1.65;
    }

    pre.shell {
      background: #0e0e10;
      color: #e4e4e7;
      border: 1px solid #2a2a2f;
      border-radius: 4px;
      padding: 14px 18px;
      font-family: var(--mono);
      font-size: 0.86rem;
      line-height: 1.6;
      overflow-x: auto;
      margin: 0;
    }
    pre.shell code { color: inherit; background: transparent; padding: 0; font-family: inherit; font-size: inherit; }

    ul.rules {
      line-height: 1.85;
      font-family: var(--serif);
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      padding-left: 22px;
    }
    ul.rules li { margin-bottom: 8px; }

    dl.breakdown {
      display: grid;
      gap: 10px;
      margin: 16px 0 24px;
    }
    dl.breakdown > div {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 80px 1fr;
      gap: 18px;
      align-items: baseline;
    }
    dl.breakdown dt {
      font-family: var(--mono);
      font-size: 1.5rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      color: var(--orange);
      text-align: right;
      margin: 0;
    }
    dl.breakdown dd {
      margin: 0;
      font-family: var(--serif);
      font-size: 0.94rem;
      line-height: 1.6;
    }

    .proof-table {
      margin: 16px 0;
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-radius: 4px;
      overflow: hidden;
      font-family: var(--mono);
      font-size: 0.85rem;
    }
    .proof-head, .proof-row {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 130px 210px 1fr 260px;
      gap: 16px;
      padding: 10px 14px;
      align-items: baseline;
    }
    .proof-head {
      background: var(--surface);
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
      font-weight: 600;
      color: var(--muted);
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 1px;
      font-size: 0.72rem;
    }
    .proof-row { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); }
    .proof-row:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
    .proof-row.partial { background: rgba(234, 179, 8, 0.06); }
    .proof-row .status { color: var(--green); font-size: 0.78rem; }
    .proof-row.partial .status { color: #a16207; }
    .proof-row .check, .proof-row .warn { display: inline-block; margin-right: 2px; }
    .proof-row .thm { font-weight: 600; color: var(--text); }
    .proof-row .what { color: var(--text); font-family: var(--serif); font-size: 0.92rem; }
    .proof-row .file a { color: var(--cyan); }
    .proof-row .file code { font-size: 0.82rem; }
    .proof-row .file .counts {
      display: block;
      margin-top: 2px;
      color: var(--muted);
      font-family: var(--mono);
      font-size: 0.72rem;
    }

    section.file-block {
      margin: 40px 0 24px;
      scroll-margin-top: 80px;
    }
    section.file-block.partial {
      border-left: 3px solid #d97706;
      padding-left: 16px;
    }
    .file-header h3 {
      margin: 0 0 8px;
      font-family: var(--mono);
      font-size: 1.15rem;
    }
    .file-header h3 code {
      background: transparent;
      padding: 0;
      font-size: inherit;
      color: var(--text);
      font-weight: 700;
    }
    .file-meta {
      display: flex;
      gap: 16px;
      align-items: center;
      font-family: var(--mono);
      font-size: 0.78rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      flex-wrap: wrap;
      margin-bottom: 6px;
    }
    .sorry-badge.zero { color: var(--green); }
    .sorry-badge.some { color: #d97706; font-weight: 600; }
    .view-gh { color: var(--cyan); }
    .file-what {
      font-family: var(--serif);
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      margin: 8px 0 14px;
      line-height: 1.6;
    }

    article.theorem {
      margin: 16px 0 20px;
      padding-left: 2px;
      scroll-margin-top: 80px;
    }
    article.theorem.has-sorry {
      border-left: 2px solid #d97706;
      padding-left: 14px;
    }
    .theorem-head {
      display: flex;
      gap: 14px;
      align-items: baseline;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
      margin-bottom: 6px;
    }
    .thm-name {
      font-family: var(--mono);
      font-size: 0.96rem;
      color: var(--text);
      font-weight: 700;
      background: transparent;
      padding: 0;
    }
    .line-link {
      font-family: var(--mono);
      font-size: 0.76rem;
      color: var(--cyan);
    }
    .hook {
      font-family: var(--serif);
      font-size: 0.92rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      margin: 4px 0 10px;
      line-height: 1.6;
    }
    .sorry-warn {
      font-size: 0.84rem;
      color: #a16207;
      font-family: var(--serif);
      background: rgba(234, 179, 8, 0.08);
      border: 1px solid rgba(234, 179, 8, 0.3);
      border-radius: 3px;
      padding: 8px 12px;
      margin: 6px 0 10px;
      line-height: 1.55;
    }

    pre.lean {
      background: #0e0e10;
      color: #e4e4e7;
      border: 1px solid #2a2a2f;
      border-radius: 4px;
      padding: 14px 18px;
      font-family: var(--mono);
      font-size: 0.82rem;
      line-height: 1.6;
      overflow-x: auto;
      margin: 8px 0;
    }
    pre.lean code {
      background: transparent;
      color: inherit;
      padding: 0;
      font-family: inherit;
      font-size: inherit;
      white-space: pre;
    }

    p.footnote {
      margin-top: 16px;
      font-size: 0.92rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      line-height: 1.75;
      border-left: 2px solid var(--border);
      padding-left: 14px;
    }

    @media (max-width: 720px) {
      .proof-head, .proof-row {
        grid-template-columns: 1fr;
        gap: 4px;
        padding: 14px;
      }
      .proof-head { display: none; }
      .proof-row .status::after { content: ' ·'; color: var(--muted); }
      dl.breakdown > div { grid-template-columns: 64px 1fr; gap: 12px; }
      dl.breakdown dt { font-size: 1.25rem; }
      pre.shell, pre.lean { font-size: 0.76rem; padding: 12px 14px; }
      .file-meta { gap: 10px; }
    }
  </style>
</Base>
